 force 12 ("<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurricane" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Hurricane">hurricane</a>-force") storm at sea, the high=
est rated on the Beaufort scale</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <b>Beaufort scale</b> (<span class=3D"rt-commentedText nowrap"><span=
 class=3D"IPA nopopups noexcerpt" lang=3D"en-fonipa"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title=3D"Help:IPA/English">/<span styl=
e=3D"border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title=3D"/=CB=88/: primary stress foll=
ows">=CB=88</span><span title=3D"'b' in 'buy'">b</span><span title=3D"/o=CA=
=8A/: 'o' in 'code'">o=CA=8A</span><span title=3D"'f' in 'find'">f</span><s=
pan title=3D"/=C9=99r/: 'er' in 'letter'">=C9=99r</span><span title=3D"'t' =
in 'tie'">t</span></span>/</a></span></span> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Help:Pronunciation_respelling_key" title=3D"Help:Pronunciation r=
espelling key"><i title=3D"English pronunciation respelling"><span style=3D=
"font-size:90%">BOH</span>-f=C9=99rt</i></a>) is an <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Empirical" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Empirical">empi=
rical</a> measure that relates <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Win=
d_speed" title=3D"Wind speed">wind speed</a> to observed conditions at sea =
or on land. Its full name is the <b>Beaufort wind force scale</b>. It was d=
evised in 1805 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Beaufort=
" title=3D"Francis Beaufort">Francis Beaufort</a>, a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrography" title=3D"Hydrography">hydrographer</a> in t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Navy" title=3D"Royal Navy=
">Royal Navy</a>. It was officially adopted by the Royal Navy and later spr=
ead internationally.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBeaufort_scale&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:FrancisBeaufort.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descrip=
tion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/06=
/FrancisBeaufort.jpg/250px-FrancisBeaufort.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"314" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1018" dat=
a-file-height=3D"1280"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Francis_Beaufort" title=3D"Francis Beaufort">Sir Francis Beaufort</a><=
/figcaption></figure>
<p>The scale that carries Beaufort's name had a long and complex evolution =
from the previous work of others (including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Daniel_Defoe" title=3D"Daniel Defoe">Daniel Defoe</a> the century=
 before).  In the 18th century, naval officers made regular weather observa=
tions, but there was no standard scale and so they could be very subjective=
&nbsp;=E2=80=94 one man's "stiff breeze" might be another's "soft breeze"=
=E2=80=94: Beaufort succeeded in standardising a scale.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Saucier-1955_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Beaufort_scale#cite_note-Saucier-1955-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The scale was devis=
ed in 1805 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Beaufort" ti=
tle=3D"Francis Beaufort">Francis Beaufort</a> (later <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Rear_admiral_(Royal_Navy)" title=3D"Rear admiral (Royal =
Navy)">Rear Admiral</a>), a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrog=
raphy" title=3D"Hydrography">hydrographer</a> and a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Navy" title=3D"Royal Navy">Royal Navy</a> officer, =
while serving on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Woolwich_(178=
5)" title=3D"HMS Woolwich (1785)">HMS&nbsp;<i>Woolwich</i></a>, and refined=
 until he was <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrographer_of_the_=
Navy" title=3D"Hydrographer of the Navy">Hydrographer of the Navy</a> in th=
e 1830s, when it was adopted officially.  It was first used during the 1831=
-1836 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_voyage_of_HMS_Beagle"=
 title=3D"Second voyage of HMS Beagle">"Darwin voyage"</a> of <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Beagle" title=3D"HMS Beagle">HMS <i>Beagle<=
/i></a> under Captain <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_FitzR=
oy" title=3D"Robert FitzRoy">Robert FitzRoy</a>, who was later to set up th=
e first <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Met_Office" title=3D"Met O=
ffice">Meteorological Office</a> in Britain giving regular weather forecast=
s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-met_office_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaufort_scale#cite_note-met_office-2"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The initial scale of 13 classes (zero to 12) did not reference <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wind_speed" title=3D"Wind speed">wind s=
peed</a> numbers, but related qualitative wind conditions to effects on the=
 sails of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frigate#Heavy_frigate"=
 title=3D"Frigate">frigate</a>, then the main ship of the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Navy" title=3D"Royal Navy">Royal Navy</a>, fr=
om "just sufficient to give steerage" to "that which no canvas sails could =
withstand".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaufort_scale#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The scale was made a standard for ship's log entries on Royal Navy v=
essels in the late 1830s and, in 1853, the Beaufort scale was accepted as g=
enerally applicable at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interna=
tional_Meteorological_Organization#History" title=3D"International Meteorol=
ogical Organization">First International Meteorological Conference in Bruss=
els</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Saucier-1955_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaufort_scale#cite_note-Saucier-1955-1">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>In 1916, to accommodate the growth of steam power, the descriptions =
were changed to how the sea, not the sails, behaved and extended to land ob=
servations. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anemometer" title=3D"A=
nemometer">Anemometer</a> rotations to scale numbers were standardised only=
 in 1923. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Simpson_(meteorol=
ogist)" title=3D"George Simpson (meteorologist)">George Simpson</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire" title=3D"Or=
der of the British Empire">CBE</a> (later Sir George Simpson), director of =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom" title=3D"Unite=
d Kingdom">UK</a> Meteorological Office, was responsible for this and for t=
he addition of the land-based descriptors.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-met_office_2-=
1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaufort_sc=
ale#cite_note-met_office-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The measures were slightly altered s=
ome decades later to improve its utility for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Meteorologist" title=3D"Meteorologist">meteorologists</a>. Nowad=
ays, meteorologists typically express wind speed in kilometres or miles per=
 hour or, for maritime and aviation purposes, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Knot_(unit)" title=3D"Knot (unit)">knots</a>, but Beaufort scal=
e terminology is still sometimes used in weather forecasts for shipping<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Beaufort_scale#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Severe_weather" title=3D"Severe weather">severe weather</=
a> warnings given to the public.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaufort_scale#cite_note-5"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Beaufort_wind_scale.png" class=3D"mw-file-des=
cription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/=
b/ba/Beaufort_wind_scale.png/250px-Beaufort_wind_scale.png" decoding=3D"asy=
nc" width=3D"250" height=3D"180" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"843" data-file-height=3D"607"></a><figcaption><div class=3D"center">Dat=
a graphic showing Beaufort wind force in scale units, knots and metres/seco=
nd</div></figcaption></figure>
<p>Wind speed on the modern Beaufort scale is based on the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empirical_relationship" title=3D"Empirical relatio=
nship">empirical relationship</a>:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaufort_scale#cite_note-6"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<ul><li><i>v</i> =3D 0.836 <i>B</i><sup>3/2</sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Metre_per_second" title=3D"Metre per second">m/s</a></li>
<li><i>v</i> =3D 1.625 <i>B</i><sup>3/2</sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Knot_(unit)" title=3D"Knot (unit)">knots</a> (<span class=3D"mw=
e-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inli=
ne mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www=
.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle =3D{\frac {13}{8}}{\sqr=
t {B^{3}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mn>13</mn>
            <mn>8</mn>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <msup>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>3</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle =3D{\frac {13=
}{8}}{\sqrt {B^{3}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/b5206bf4aa29c59339ae94b339d2edf0a092d6da" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.838ex; width:10.756ex; height:5.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle =
=3D{\frac {13}{8}}{\sqrt {B^{3}}}}"></span>)</li></ul>
<p>where <i>v</i> is the equivalent wind speed at 10 metres above the sea s=
urface and <i>B</i> is Beaufort scale number. For example, <i>B</i> =3D 9.5=
 is related to 24.5&nbsp;m/s which is equal to the lower limit of "10 Beauf=
ort". Using this formula the highest winds in hurricanes would be 23 in the=
 scale. F1 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tornado" title=3D"Torna=
do">tornadoes</a> on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fujita_sc=
ale" title=3D"Fujita scale">Fujita scale</a> and T2 <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/TORRO_scale" title=3D"TORRO scale">TORRO scale</a> also b=
egin roughly at the end of level 12 of the Beaufort scale, but are independ=
ent scales, although the TORRO scale wind values are based on the 3/2 power=
 law relating wind velocity to Beaufort force.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaufort_scale#cite=
_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wave_height" title=3D"Wave =
height">Wave heights</a> in the scale are for conditions in the open ocean,=
 not along the shore.
</p>
