<p>The Beaufort scale is neither an exact nor an objective scale; it was ba=
sed on visual and subjective observation of a ship and of the sea. The corr=
esponding integral wind speeds were determined later, but conversions have =
not been made official.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Extended_scale">Extended sc=
ale</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBeaufort=
_scale&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Extended s=
cale"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>The Beaufort scale was extended in 1946 when forces 13 to 17 were added.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Saucier-1955_1-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaufort_scale#cite_note-Saucier-1955-1"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 However, forces 13 to 17 were intended to apply only to special cases, suc=
h as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tropical_cyclone" title=3D"Tr=
opical cyclone">tropical cyclones</a>. Nowadays, the extended scale is used=
 in Taiwan,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaufort_scale#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> mainland Chin=
a<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Beaufort_scale#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and Vietnam,<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
eaufort_scale#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which are often affected by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Typhoon" title=3D"Typhoon">typhoons</a>. =
Internationally, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Meteoro=
logical_Organization" title=3D"World Meteorological Organization">World Met=
eorological Organization</a> Manual on Marine Meteorological Services (2012=
 edition) defined the Beaufort Scale only up to force 12 and there was no r=
ecommendation on the use of the extended scale.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaufort_scale#cit=
e_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
